{"query": "What are the effects on butterfly and moth communities of opening up forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning?", "summary": "Opening forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning has differential effects on butterfly and moth communities. Clearing or opening patches in forests generally benefits butterflies while having mixed effects on moths. Studies found that cleared patches had greater species richness of butterflies but lower species richness of moths than unmanaged patches, coppiced woodland, or closed canopy forest (Action 3938). Larger cleared patches supported higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than undisturbed forest, while smaller patches did not show this effect (Action 3938). Butterfly abundance was consistently higher in cleared patches, with specific benefits documented for species including chequered blue, woodland brown, high brown fritillary, and small pearl-bordered fritillary (Action 3938). A European review found that clearing small patches in forests benefitted 19 out of 67 butterfly species of conservation concern (Action 3938).

Coppicing woodland showed strong positive effects for butterflies but negative effects for moths. Coppiced woodland had greater species richness of butterflies than unmanaged woodland but lower species richness of macro-moths than mature forest (Action 3939). The abundance of butterflies was higher in coppiced woodland than unmanaged woodland, with particular benefits for heath fritillary, pearl-bordered fritillary, and small pearl-bordered fritillary (Action 3939). Coppice age matters, with woodland coppiced 2-4 years ago supporting higher butterfly abundance than older coppice (Action 3939). However, macro-moth abundance was lower in coppiced woodland than mature forest (Action 3939).

Forest thinning combined with other management practices showed positive effects for butterflies. Coniferous woodland that had been thinned along with prescribed burning, mulching, or nearby felling had greater species richness and higher abundance of butterflies than unmanaged woodland (Action 3940). In tropical forests, thinning had neutral effects, with managed forests showing similar species richness and abundance of fruit-feeding butterflies to unmanaged forests (Action 3940). One study found that partially-cleared forest plots had higher butterfly but lower moth species richness than closed-canopy forest plots (Action 3940).", "action_ids": ["3938","3939","3940"]}

