  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from action documents, butterfly population re-establishment through translocation and captive-release shows mixed long-term success rates. For captive-bred butterfly releases (Action ID 3914), six studies in the UK, USA, Poland and Slovakia reported that populations released as eggs, caterpillars, pupae and adults persisted for 2-28 years and increased in abundance, sometimes with continued captive-rearing of wild-laid caterpillars or supplemented by further releases. However, two UK studies reported that captive-bred large copper and belted beauty moth populations died out one, two or 12 years after release, or required further releases to survive. One replicated UK study found that only three of 10 captive-bred barberry carpet moth populations established, with at least one persisting for five years. A critical finding from a review across the UK and Ireland showed that only 25% of captive-bred and translocated butterfly populations survived for more than 3 years, 38% died out within that time, and only 8% were known to have survived for more than 10 years.\n\nFor translocation to re-establish populations (Action ID 3909), eight studies reported that translocated populations of adult butterflies and Fisher's estuarine moth eggs persisted for 2-12 years and increased in abundance. However, three studies found that some translocated populations persisted for 1-49 years and colonized new sites, while other populations died out within 0-7 years. One UK and Ireland review found identical success rates to captive-breeding: 25% of translocated populations survived for at least three years, 38% died out within that time, and only 8% survived for more than 10 years. Another review reported that translocated large copper populations survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation by further releases. Studies also found that translocated large copper caterpillars had higher survival rates than released